data.footnote: Included "Take A Lap" and "Coach on Rainstick" bingo balls. Each band member and Coach took a lap around the barn.
data.jamchart_notes: A first jam that stays within bounds but explodes with the power of the sun leads into a second jam where the band members each have to "Take a Lap". Peter steps out early with aggressive guitar riffing as Rick and the drums lock in on each other as the music takes on a runaway freight train vibe. When Spuds finally takes his turn, Jeff picks up the beat out of the fragmented space and crafts an airy, major-key jam. Coach hops on rainstick and Rick adds some vocalizing as it slowly and patiently winds down.
data.shownotes: This show was the first night of the Bingo Tour. The whole setlist was chosen based on random draws of bingo balls with different songs or gimmicks on them. This was Jeff's first show with the band.

Still pretty much Type I throughout but a very fun and groovy listen. Peter hits the keys right at the end with hints of Ted Tapes riffing as they > to an explosive "Red Bird."

data.jamchart_notes: After Peter tells crowd they have one more song, Rick rips back into a second Drive jam to end the show. A fiery theme develops and eventually morphs into the "(dawn)" finish. Incredible spontaneous moment.

Cotter's first big jam and the band does not hold back one iota. First developing a ripping dual-guitar jam for several minutes - very active Trevor - before Cotter seamlessly transitions into the "second jam." Patiently builds into a bliss motif reminiscent of the ending of "SOS," peaking massively and concluding just short of the 31-minute mark.
data.shownotes: This was Cotter's first show as a member of Goose. Eminence Front was played for the first time since November 13, 2021 (180 shows).

data.jamchart_notes: Second "Drive" of the year and second to pass 30 minutes. Hangs out in fast-paced two-guitar funk zones until the 15th minute, when Rick leads into a more atmospheric zone atop a bed of Peter's synth. Trevor gets LOW as the band finds an ascending riff akin to "Time to Flee" and works it for a while. Eventually finds its way into a piano-forward zone that seems to hint at "Factory Fiction" for a while. Lands smoothly in a set-closing "Give it Time."

data.jamchart_notes: After some quick dual-guitar riffing, Peter pivots to OB-6 and transforms the jam within a few seconds. The band goes full Ted Tapes for a while, luxuriating in an almost "Dragonfly"-like space, before Rick steers into a build based around a repeating melody. Taking on qualities similar to the final section of the 4/14/23 "Hungersite," Goose delivers one of the most breathtakingly beautiful peaks of their career to date.

data.jamchart_notes: The late-blooming younger brother of 24's monstrous high-school quarterback and homecoming king, "Cap Drive." The sibling resemblance is unmistabkle, with the same prominent good looks and form. But while 24's two-guitar Goose section immediately unleashes a colossal wall of sound, this one ambles through the halls of adolescent uncertainty before finally finding its senior-year stride — ignited by Rick’s delicate yet forceful guitar-work, Pete’s sudden organ attack, and Cotter’s thunderous drumming.
